In the Roslyn C# compiler, BoundNode.Syntax can, with one exception, never be null.  Only a synthesized node that is a (hidden) sequence point can have a null syntax.  We currently annotate Syntax as non-null, and use `!` in the one or two places where null comes in.

We cannot put a `new Syntax` property on `BoundSequencePoint` that hides the one from the base class and returns `Syntax?`, as that would prevent the auto-generated Update method from compiling without a warning.

@333fred suggests "perhaps we should add a way to add a suppression to the generated Update method. Can you file a bug to track? If we're lying about what Syntax can return, we're likely going to get bitten by it at some point."

